# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metallurgy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In metallurgy and materials science, **annealing** is a heat treatment that alters the physical and sometimes chemical properties of a material to increase its ductility and reduce its hardness, making it more workable.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] It involves heating a material above its recrystallization temperature, maintaining a suitable temperature for an appropriate amount of time, and then cooling.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In annealing, atoms migrate in the crystal lattice and the number of dislocations decreases, leading to a change in ductility and hardness.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] As the material cools it recrystallizes.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] For many alloys, including carbon steel, the crystal grain size and phase composition, which ultimately determine the material properties, are dependent on the heating rate and cooling rate.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Hot working or cold working after the annealing process alters the metal structure, so further heat treatments may be used to achieve the properties required.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] With knowledge of the composition and phase diagram, heat treatment can be used to adjust from harder and more brittle to softer and more ductile.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In the case of ferrous metals, such as steel, annealing is performed by heating the material (generally until glowing) for a while and then slowly letting it cool to room temperature in still air.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Copper, silver and brass can be either cooled slowly in air, or quickly by quenching in water.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In this fashion, the metal is softened and prepared for further work such as shaping, stamping, or forming.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Many other materials, including glass and plastic films, use annealing to improve the finished properties.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Annealing occurs by the diffusion of atoms within a solid material, so that the material progresses towards its equilibrium state.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Heat increases the rate of diffusion by providing the energy needed to break bonds.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The movement of atoms has the effect of redistributing and eradicating the dislocations in metals and (to a lesser extent) in ceramics.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This alteration to existing dislocations allows a metal object to deform more easily, increasing its ductility.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The amount of process-initiating Gibbs free energy in a deformed metal is also reduced by the annealing process.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In practice and industry, this reduction of Gibbs free energy is termed *stress relief*.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The relief of internal stresses is a thermodynamically spontaneous process; however, at room temperatures, it is a very slow process.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The high temperatures at which annealing occurs serve to accelerate this process.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The reaction that facilitates returning the cold-worked metal to its stress-free state has many reaction pathways, mostly involving the elimination of lattice vacancy gradients within the body of the metal.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The creation of lattice vacancies is governed by the Arrhenius equation, and the migration/diffusion of lattice vacancies are governed by Fick's laws of diffusion.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In steel, there is a decarburization mechanism that can be described as three distinct events: the reaction at the steel surface, the interstitial diffusion of carbon atoms and the dissolution of carbides within the steel.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The three stages of the annealing process that proceed as the temperature of the material is increased are: **recovery**, **recrystallization**, and **grain growth**.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The first stage is recovery, and it results in softening of the metal through removal of primarily linear defects called *dislocations* and the internal stresses they cause.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Recovery occurs at the lower temperature stage of all annealing processes and before the appearance of new strain-free grains.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The second stage is recrystallization, where new strain-free grains nucleate and grow to replace those deformed by internal stresses.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] If annealing is allowed to continue once recrystallization has completed, then grain growth (the third stage) occurs.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In grain growth, the microstructure starts to coarsen and may cause the metal to lose a substantial part of its original strength.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This can however be regained with hardening.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The high temperature of annealing may result in oxidation of the metal's surface, resulting in scale.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] If scale must be avoided, annealing is carried out in a special atmosphere, such as with endothermic gas (a mixture of carbon monoxide, hydrogen gas, and nitrogen gas).
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Annealing is also done in forming gas, a mixture of hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The magnetic properties of mu-metal are introduced by annealing the alloy in a hydrogen atmosphere.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Typically, large ovens are used for the annealing process.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The inside of the oven is large enough to place the workpiece in a position to receive maximum exposure to the circulating heated air.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] For high volume process annealing, gas fired conveyor furnaces are often used.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] For large workpieces or high quantity parts, car-bottom furnaces are used so workers can easily move the parts in and out.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Once the annealing process is successfully completed, workpieces are sometimes left in the oven so the parts cool in a controllable way.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] While some workpieces are left in the oven to cool in a controlled fashion, other materials and alloys are removed from the oven.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Once removed from the oven, the workpieces are often quickly cooled off in a process known as quench hardening.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Typical methods of quench hardening materials involve media such as air, water, oil, or salt.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Salt is used as a medium for quenching usually in the form of brine (salt water).
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Brine provides faster cooling rates than water.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This is because when an object is quenched in water steam bubbles form on the surface of the object reducing the surface area the water is in contact with.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The salt in the brine reduces the formation of steam bubbles on the object's surface, meaning there is a larger surface area of the object in contact with the water, thus facilitating better conduction of heat from the object to the surrounding water.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Quench hardening is generally applicable to some ferrous alloys, but not copper alloys.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In the semiconductor industry, silicon wafers are annealed to repair atomic level disorder from steps like ion implantation.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In the process step, dopant atoms, usually boron, phosphorus or arsenic, move into substitutional positions in the crystal lattice, which allows these dopant atoms to function properly as dopants in the semiconducting material.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Process annealing, also called *intermediate annealing*, *subcritical annealing*, or *in-process annealing*, is a heat treatment cycle that restores some of the ductility to a product being cold-worked so it can be cold-worked further without breaking.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The temperature range for process annealing ranges from 260 °C (500 °F) to 760 °C (1400 °F), depending on the alloy in question.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This process is mainly suited for low-carbon steel.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The material is heated up to a temperature just below the lower critical temperature of steel.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Cold-worked steel normally tends to possess increased hardness and decreased ductility, making it difficult to work.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Process annealing tends to improve these characteristics.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This is mainly carried out on cold-rolled steel like wire-drawn steel, centrifugally cast ductile iron pipe etc.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] A full annealing typically results in the second most ductile state a metal can assume for metal alloy.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Its purpose is to originate a uniform and stable microstructure that most closely resembles the metal's phase diagram equilibrium microstructure, thus letting the metal attain relatively low levels of hardness, yield strength and ultimate strength with high plasticity and toughness.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] To perform a full anneal on a steel for example, steel is heated to slightly above the austenitic temperature and held for sufficient time to allow the material to fully form austenite or austenite-cementite grain structure.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The material is then allowed to cool very slowly so that the equilibrium microstructure is obtained.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In most cases this means the material is allowed to furnace cool (the furnace is turned off and the steel is let cool down inside) but in some cases it is air cooled.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The cooling rate of the steel has to be sufficiently slow so as to not let the austenite transform into bainite or martensite, but rather have it completely transform to pearlite and ferrite or cementite.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This means that steels that are very hardenable (i.e. tend to form martensite under moderately low cooling rates) have to be furnace cooled.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The details of the process depend on the type of metal and the precise alloy involved.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] In any case the result is a more ductile material but a lower yield strength and a lower tensile strength.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This process is also called LP annealing for *lamellar pearlite* in the steel industry as opposed to a *process anneal*, which does not specify a microstructure and only has the goal of softening the material.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Often the material to be machined is annealed, and then subject to further heat treatment to achieve the final desired properties.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Resistive heating can be used to efficiently anneal copper wire; the heating system employs a controlled electrical short circuit.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] It can be advantageous because it does not require a temperature-regulated furnace like other methods of annealing.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The process consists of two conductive pulleys (*step pulleys*), which the wire passes across after it is drawn.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The two pulleys have an electrical potential across them, which causes the wire to form a short circuit.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The Joule effect causes the temperature of the wire to rise to approximately 400 °C.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] This temperature is affected by the rotational speed of the pulleys, the ambient temperature, and the voltage applied.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] The constant *K* depends on the diameter of the pulleys and the resistivity of the copper.
[src:metallurgy/annealing-materials-science] Purely in terms of the temperature of the copper wire, an increase in the speed of the wire through the pulley system has the same effect as a decrease in resistance.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Metallic materials consist of a microstructure of small crystals called "grains" or crystallites.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The nature of the grains (i.e. grain size and composition) is one of the most effective factors that can determine the overall mechanical behavior of the metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Heat treatment provides an efficient way to manipulate the properties of the metal by controlling the rate of diffusion and the rate of cooling within the microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Heat treating is often used to alter the mechanical properties of a metallic alloy, manipulating properties such as the hardness, strength, toughness, ductility, and elasticity.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] There are two mechanisms that may change an alloy's properties during heat treatment: the formation of martensite causes the crystals to deform intrinsically, and the diffusion mechanism causes changes in the homogeneity of the alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The crystal structure consists of atoms that are grouped in a very specific arrangement, called a lattice.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In most elements, this order will rearrange itself, depending on conditions like temperature and pressure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This rearrangement called allotropy or polymorphism, may occur several times, at many different temperatures for a particular metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In alloys, this rearrangement may cause an element that will not normally dissolve into the base metal to suddenly become soluble, while a reversal of the allotropy will make the elements either partially or completely insoluble.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When in the soluble state, the process of diffusion causes the atoms of the dissolved element to spread out, attempting to form a homogenous distribution within the crystals of the base metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If the alloy is cooled to an insoluble state, the atoms of the dissolved constituents (solutes) may migrate out of the solution.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This type of diffusion, called precipitation, leads to nucleation, where the migrating atoms group together at the grain-boundaries.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This forms a microstructure generally consisting of two or more distinct phases.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] After heating the steel to the austenite phase and then quenching it in water, the microstructure will be in the martensitic phase.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is due to the fact that the steel will change from the austenite phase to the martensite phase after quenching.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Some pearlite or ferrite may be present if the quench did not rapidly cool off all the steel.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Unlike iron-based alloys, most heat-treatable alloys do not experience a ferrite transformation.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In these alloys, the nucleation at the grain-boundaries often reinforces the structure of the crystal matrix.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Typically a slow process, depending on temperature, this is often referred to as "age hardening".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Many metals and non-metals exhibit a martensite transformation when cooled quickly (with external media like oil, polymer, water, etc.).
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When a metal is cooled very quickly, the insoluble atoms may not be able to migrate out of the solution in time.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is called a "diffusionless transformation." When the crystal matrix changes to its low-temperature arrangement, the atoms of the solute become trapped within the lattice.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The trapped atoms prevent the crystal matrix from completely changing into its low-temperature allotrope, creating shearing stresses within the lattice.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When some alloys are cooled quickly, such as steel, the martensite transformation hardens the metal, while in others, like aluminum, the alloy becomes softer.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The specific composition of an alloy system will usually have a great effect on the results of heat treating.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If the percentage of each constituent is just right, the alloy will form a single, continuous microstructure upon cooling.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, If the percentage of the solutes varies from the eutectoid mixture, two or more different microstructures will usually form simultaneously.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A hypo eutectoid solution contains less of the solute than the eutectoid mix, while a hypereutectoid solution contains more.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A eutectoid (eutectic-like) alloy is similar in behavior to a eutectic alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A *eutectic* alloy is characterized by having a single melting point.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This melting point is lower than that of any of the constituents, and no change in the mixture will lower the melting point any further.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When a molten eutectic alloy is cooled, all of the constituents will crystallize into their respective phases at the same temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A **eutectoid alloy** is similar, but the phase change occurs, not from a liquid, but from a solid solution.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Upon cooling a eutectoid alloy from the solution temperature, the constituents will separate into different crystal phases, forming a single microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A eutectoid steel, for example, contains 0.77% carbon.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Upon cooling slowly, the solution of iron and carbon (a single phase called austenite) will separate into platelets of the phases ferrite and cementite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This forms a layered microstructure called pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Since pearlite is harder than iron, the degree of softness achievable is typically limited to that produced by the pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Similarly, the hardenability is limited by the continuous martensitic microstructure formed when cooled very fast.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A hypoeutectic alloy has two separate melting points.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Both are above the eutectic melting point for the system but are below the melting points of any constituent forming the system.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Between these two melting points, the alloy will exist as part solid and part liquid.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The constituent with the higher melting point will solidify first.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When completely solidified, a hypoeutectic alloy will often be in a solid solution.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Similarly, a **hypoeutectoid alloy** has two critical temperatures, called "arrests".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Between these two temperatures, the alloy will exist partly as the solution and partly as a separate crystallizing phase, called the "pro eutectoid phase".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These two temperatures are called the upper (A3) and lower (A1) transformation temperatures.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] As the solution cools from the upper transformation temperature toward an insoluble state, the excess base metal will often be forced to "crystallize-out", becoming the pro eutectoid.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This will occur until the remaining concentration of solutes reaches the eutectoid level, which will then crystallize as a separate microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] For example, a hypoeutectoid steel contains less than 0.77% carbon.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Upon cooling a hypoeutectoid steel from the austenite transformation temperature, small islands of proeutectoid-ferrite will form.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These will continue to grow and the carbon will recede until the eutectoid concentration in the rest of the steel is reached.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This eutectoid mixture will then crystallize as a microstructure of pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Since ferrite is softer than pearlite, the two microstructures combine to increase the ductility of the alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Consequently, the hardenability of the alloy is lowered.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A hypereutectic alloy also has different melting points.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, between these points, it is the constituent with the higher melting point that will be solid.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Similarly, a **hypereutectoid alloy** has two critical temperatures.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When cooling a hypereutectoid alloy from the upper transformation temperature, it will usually be the excess solutes that crystallize-out first, forming the pro-eutectoid.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This continues until the concentration in the remaining alloy becomes eutectoid, which then crystallizes into a separate microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A hypereutectoid steel contains more than 0.77% carbon.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When slowly cooling hypereutectoid steel, the cementite will begin to crystallize first.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When the remaining steel becomes eutectoid in composition, it will crystallize into pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Since cementite is much harder than pearlite, the alloy has greater hardenability at a cost in ductility.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Proper heat treating requires precise control over temperature, time held at a certain temperature and cooling rate.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] With the exception of stress-relieving, tempering, and aging, most heat treatments begin by heating an alloy beyond a certain transformation, or arrest (A), temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This temperature is referred to as an "arrest" because at the A temperature the metal experiences a period of hysteresis.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] At this point, all of the heat energy is used to cause the crystal change, so the temperature stops rising for a short time (arrests) and then continues climbing once the change is complete.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Therefore, the alloy must be heated above the critical temperature for a transformation to occur.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The alloy will usually be held at this temperature long enough for the heat to completely penetrate the alloy, thereby bringing it into a complete solid solution.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Iron, for example, has four critical-temperatures, depending on carbon content.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Pure iron in its alpha (room temperature) state changes to nonmagnetic gamma-iron at its A2 temperature, and weldable delta-iron at its A4 temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, as carbon is added, becoming steel, the A2 temperature splits into the A3 temperature, also called the austenitizing temperature (all phases become austenite, a solution of gamma iron and carbon) and its A1 temperature (austenite changes into pearlite upon cooling).
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Between these upper and lower temperatures the pro eutectoid phase forms upon cooling.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Because a smaller grain size usually enhances mechanical properties, such as toughness, shear strength and tensile strength, these metals are often heated to a temperature that is just above the upper critical temperature, in order to prevent the grains of solution from growing too large.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] For instance, when steel is heated above the upper critical-temperature, small grains of austenite form.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These grow larger as the temperature is increased.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When cooled very quickly, during a martensite transformation, the austenite grain-size directly affects the martensitic grain-size.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Larger grains have large grain-boundaries, which serve as weak spots in the structure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The grain size is usually controlled to reduce the probability of breakage.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The diffusion transformation is very time-dependent.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Cooling a metal will usually suppress the precipitation to a much lower temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Austenite, for example, usually only exists above the upper critical temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, if the austenite is cooled quickly enough, the transformation may be suppressed for hundreds of degrees below the lower critical temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Such austenite is highly unstable and, if given enough time, will precipitate into various microstructures of ferrite and cementite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The cooling rate can be used to control the rate of grain growth or can even be used to produce partially martensitic microstructures.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, the martensite transformation is time-independent.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If the alloy is cooled to the martensite transformation (Ms) temperature before other microstructures can fully form, the transformation will usually occur at just under the speed of sound.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When austenite is cooled extremely slowly, it will form large ferrite crystals filled with spherical inclusions of cementite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This microstructure is referred to as "sphereoidite".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If cooled a little faster, then coarse pearlite will form.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Even faster, and fine pearlite will form.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If cooled even faster, bainite will form, with more complete bainite transformation occurring depending on the time held above martensite start Ms.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Similarly, these microstructures will also form, if cooled to a specific temperature and then held there for a certain time.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Most non-ferrous alloys are also heated in order to form a solution.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Most often, these are then cooled very quickly to produce a martensite transformation, putting the solution into a supersaturated state.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The alloy, being in a much softer state, may then be cold worked.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This causes work hardening that increases the strength and hardness of the alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Moreover, the defects caused by plastic deformation tend to speed up precipitation, increasing the hardness beyond what is normal for the alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Even if not cold worked, the solutes in these alloys will usually precipitate, although the process may take much longer.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Sometimes these metals are then heated to a temperature that is below the lower critical (A1) temperature, preventing recrystallization, in order to speed-up the precipitation.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Complex heat treating schedules, or "cycles", are often devised by metallurgists to optimize an alloy's mechanical properties.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In the aerospace industry, a superalloy may undergo five or more different heat treating operations to develop the desired properties.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This can lead to quality problems depending on the accuracy of the furnace's temperature controls and timer.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These operations can usually be divided into several basic techniques.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Annealing consists of heating a metal to a specific temperature and then cooling at a rate that will produce a refined microstructure, either fully or partially separating the constituents.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Annealing is most often used to soften a metal for cold working, to improve machinability, or to enhance properties like electrical conductivity.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In ferrous alloys, annealing is usually accomplished by heating the metal beyond the upper critical temperature and then cooling very slowly, resulting in the formation of pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In both pure metals and many alloys that cannot be heat treated, annealing is used to remove the hardness caused by cold working.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The metal is heated to a temperature where recrystallization can occur, thereby repairing the defects caused by plastic deformation.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In these metals, the rate of cooling will usually have little effect.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Most non-ferrous alloys that are heat-treatable are also annealed to relieve the hardness of cold working.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These may be slowly cooled to allow full precipitation of the constituents and produce a refined microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Ferrous alloys are usually either "full annealed" or "process annealed".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Full annealing requires very slow cooling rates, in order to form coarse pearlite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In process annealing, the cooling rate may be faster; up to, and including normalizing.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The main goal of process annealing is to produce a uniform microstructure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Non-ferrous alloys are often subjected to a variety of annealing techniques, including "recrystallization annealing", "partial annealing", "full annealing", and "final annealing".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Not all annealing techniques involve recrystallization, such as stress relieving.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Normalizing is a technique used to provide uniformity in grain size and composition (equiaxed crystals) throughout an alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The term is often used for ferrous alloys that have been austenitized and then cooled in the open air.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Normalizing not only produces pearlite but also martensite and sometimes bainite, which gives harder and stronger steel but with less ductility for the same composition than full annealing.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In the normalizing process the steel is heated to about 40 degrees Celsius above its upper critical temperature limit, held at this temperature for some time, and then cooled in air.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Stress-relieving is a technique to remove or reduce the internal stresses created in metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These stresses may be caused in a number of ways, ranging from cold working to non-uniform cooling.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Stress-relieving is usually accomplished by heating a metal below the lower critical temperature and then cooling uniformly.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Stress relieving is commonly used on items like air tanks, boilers and other pressure vessels, to remove a portion of the stresses created during the welding process.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Some metals are classified as *precipitation hardening metals*.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When a precipitation hardening alloy is quenched, its alloying elements will be trapped in solution, resulting in a soft metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Aging a "solutionized" metal will allow the alloying elements to diffuse through the microstructure and form intermetallic particles.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These intermetallic particles will nucleate and fall out of the solution and act as a reinforcing phase, thereby increasing the strength of the alloy.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Alloys may age " naturally" meaning that the precipitates form at room temperature, or they may age "artificially" when precipitates only form at elevated temperatures.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In some applications, naturally aging alloys may be stored in a freezer to prevent hardening until after further operations - assembly of rivets, for example, maybe easier with a softer part.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Examples of precipitation hardening alloys include 2000 series, 6000 series, and 7000 series aluminium alloy, as well as some superalloys and some stainless steels.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Steels that harden by aging are typically referred to as maraging steels, from a combination of the term "martensite aging".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Quenching is a process of cooling a metal at a rapid rate.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is most often done to produce a martensite transformation.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In ferrous alloys, this will often produce a harder metal, while non-ferrous alloys will usually become softer than normal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] To harden by quenching, a metal (usually steel or cast iron) must be heated above the upper critical temperature (Steel: above 815~900 degrees Celsius) and then quickly cooled.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Depending on the alloy and other considerations (such as concern for maximum hardness vs. cracking and distortion), cooling may be done with forced air or other gases, (such as nitrogen).
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Liquids may be used, due to their better thermal conductivity, such as oil, water, a polymer dissolved in water, or a brine.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Upon being rapidly cooled, a portion of austenite (dependent on alloy composition) will transform to martensite, a hard, brittle crystalline structure.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The quenched hardness of a metal depends on its chemical composition and quenching method.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Cooling speeds, from fastest to slowest, go from brine, polymer (i.e. mixtures of water + glycol polymers), freshwater, oil, and forced air.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Some Beta titanium based alloys have also shown similar trends of increased strength through rapid cooling.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, most non-ferrous metals, like alloys of copper, aluminum, or nickel, and some high alloy steels such as austenitic stainless steel (304, 316), produce an opposite effect when these are quenched: they soften.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Austenitic stainless steels must be quenched to become fully corrosion resistant, as they work-harden significantly.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Untempered martensitic steel, while very hard, is too brittle to be useful for most applications.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A method for alleviating this problem is called tempering.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Most applications require that quenched parts be tempered.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Tempering consists of heating steel below the lower critical temperature, (often from 400˚F to 1105˚F or 205˚C to 595˚C, depending on the desired results), to impart some toughness.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Higher tempering temperatures (maybe up to 1,300˚F or 700˚C, depending on the alloy and application) are sometimes used to impart further ductility, although some yield strength is lost.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Tempering may also be performed on normalized steels.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Other methods of tempering consist of quenching to a specific temperature, which is above the martensite start temperature, and then holding it there until pure bainite can form or internal stresses can be relieved.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These include austempering and martempering.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Steel that has been freshly ground or polished will form oxide layers when heated.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] At a very specific temperature, the iron oxide will form a layer with a very specific thickness, causing thin-film interference.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This causes colors to appear on the surface of the steel.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] As the temperature is increased, the iron oxide layer grows in thickness, changing the color.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These colors, called tempering colors, have been used for centuries to gauge the temperature of the metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The tempering colors can be used to judge the final properties of the tempered steel.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Very hard tools are often tempered in the light to the dark straw range, whereas springs are often tempered to the blue.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, the final hardness of the tempered steel will vary, depending on the composition of the steel.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Higher-carbon tool steel will remain much harder after tempering than spring steel (of slightly less carbon) when tempered at the same temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The oxide film will also increase in thickness over time.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Therefore, steel that has been held at 400˚F for a very long time may turn brown or purple, even though the temperature never exceeded that needed to produce a light straw color.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Other factors affecting the final outcome are oil films on the surface and the type of heat source used.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Many heat treating methods have been developed to alter the properties of only a portion of an object.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These tend to consist of either cooling different areas of an alloy at different rates, by quickly heating in a localized area and then quenching, by thermochemical diffusion, or by tempering different areas of an object at different temperatures, such as in differential tempering.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Some techniques allow different areas of a single object to receive different heat treatments.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] It is common in high quality knives and swords.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The Chinese jian is one of the earliest known examples of this, and the Japanese katana may be the most widely known.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The Nepalese Khukuri is another example.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This technique uses an insulating layer, like layers of clay, to cover the areas that are to remain soft.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The areas to be hardened are left exposed, allowing only certain parts of the steel to fully harden when quenched.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Flame hardening is used to harden only a portion of the metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Unlike differential hardening, where the entire piece is heated and then cooled at different rates, in flame hardening, only a portion of the metal is heated before quenching.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is usually easier than differential hardening, but often produces an extremely brittle zone between the heated metal and the unheated metal, as cooling at the edge of this heat-affected zone is extremely rapid.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Induction hardening is a surface hardening technique in which the surface of the metal is heated very quickly, using a no-contact method of induction heating.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The alloy is then quenched, producing a martensite transformation at the surface while leaving the underlying metal unchanged.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This creates a very hard, wear-resistant surface while maintaining the proper toughness in the majority of the object.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Crankshaft journals are a good example of an induction hardened surface.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Case hardening is a thermochemical diffusion process in which an alloying element, most commonly carbon or nitrogen, diffuses into the surface of a monolithic metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The resulting interstitial solid solution is harder than the base material, which improves wear resistance without sacrificing toughness.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Laser surface engineering is a surface treatment with high versatility, selectivity and novel properties.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Since the cooling rate is very high in laser treatment, metastable even metallic glass can be obtained by this method.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Although quenching steel causes the austenite to transform into martensite, all of the austenite usually does not transform.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Some austenite crystals will remain unchanged even after quenching below the martensite finish (Mf) temperature.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Further transformation of the austenite into martensite can be induced by slowly cooling the metal to extremely low temperatures.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Cold treating generally consists of cooling the steel to around -115˚F (-81˚C), but does not eliminate all of the austenite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Cryogenic treating usually consists of cooling to much lower temperatures, often in the range of -315˚F (-192˚C), to transform most of the austenite into martensite.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The process is often used for tools, bearings, or other items that require good wear resistance.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] However, it is usually only effective in high-carbon or high-alloy steels in which more than 10% austenite is retained after quenching.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The heating of steel is sometimes used as a method to alter the carbon content.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When steel is heated in an oxidizing environment, the oxygen combines with the iron to form an iron-oxide layer, which protects the steel from decarburization.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When the steel turns to austenite, however, the oxygen combines with iron to form a slag, which provides no protection from decarburization.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The formation of slag and scale actually increases decarburization, because the iron oxide keeps oxygen in contact with the decarburization zone even after the steel is moved into an oxygen-free environment, such as the coals of a forge.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Thus, the carbon atoms begin combining with the surrounding scale and slag to form both carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide, which is released into the air.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Steel contains a relatively small percentage of carbon, which can migrate freely within the gamma iron.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When austenitized steel is exposed to air for long periods of time, the carbon content in the steel can be lowered.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is the opposite from what happens when steel is heated in a reducing environment, in which carbon slowly diffuses further into the metal.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] In an oxidizing environment, the carbon can readily diffuse outwardly, so austenitized steel is very susceptible to decarburization.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This is often used for cast steel, where a high carbon content is needed for casting, but a lower carbon content is desired in the finished product.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] It is often used on cast iron to produce malleable cast iron, in a process called "white tempering".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This tendency to decarburize is often a problem in other operations, such as blacksmithing, where it becomes more desirable to austenitize the steel for the shortest amount of time possible to prevent too much decarburization.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Usually the end condition is specified instead of the process used in heat treatment.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Case hardening is specified by "hardness" and "case depth".
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The case depth can be specified in two ways: total case depth or effective case depth.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The total case depth is the true depth of the case.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] For most alloys, the effective case depth is the depth of the case that has a hardness equivalent of HRC50; however, some alloys specify a different hardness (40-60 HRC) at effective case depth; this is checked on a Tukon microhardness tester.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This value can be roughly approximated as 65% of the total case depth; however, the chemical composition and hardenability can affect this approximation.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If neither type of case depth is specified the total case depth is assumed.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] For case hardened parts the specification should have a tolerance of at least ±0.005 in (0.13 mm).
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If the part is to be ground after heat treatment, the case depth is assumed to be after grinding.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The Rockwell hardness scale used for the specification depends on the depth of the total case depth, as shown in the table below.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Usually, hardness is measured on the Rockwell "C" scale, but the load used on the scale will penetrate through the case if the case is less than 0.030 in (0.76 mm).
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Using Rockwell "C" for a thinner case will result in a false reading.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] For cases that are less than 0.015 in (0.38 mm) thick a Rockwell scale cannot reliably be used, so *file hard* is specified instead.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] File hard is approximately equivalent to 58 HRC.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] When specifying the hardness either a range should be given or the minimum hardness specified.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] If a range is specified at least 5 points should be given.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Only hardness is listed for through hardening.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] It is usually in the form of HRC with at least a five-point range.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The hardness for an annealing process is usually listed on the HRB scale as a maximum value.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] It is a process to refine grain size, improve strength, remove residual stress, and affect the electromagnetic properties...
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Furnaces used for heat treatment can be split into two broad categories: batch furnaces and continuous furnaces.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Batch furnaces are usually manually loaded and unloaded, whereas continuous furnaces have an automatic conveying system to provide a constant load into the furnace chamber.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Batch systems usually consist of an insulated chamber with a steel shell, a heating system, and an access door to the chamber.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Many basic box-type furnaces have been upgraded to a semi-continuous batch furnace with the addition of integrated quench tanks and slow-cool chambers.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] These upgraded furnaces are a very commonly used piece of equipment for heat-treating.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Also known as a " bogie hearth", the car furnace is an extremely large batch furnace.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The floor is constructed as an insulated movable car that is moved in and out of the furnace for loading and unloading.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The car is usually sealed using sand seals or solid seals when in position.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Due to the difficulty in getting a sufficient seal, car furnaces are usually used for non-atmosphere processes.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Similar in type to the car furnace, except that the car and hearth are rolled into position beneath the furnace and raised by means of a motor-driven mechanism, elevator furnaces can handle large heavy loads and often eliminate the need for any external cranes and transfer mechanisms.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Bell furnaces have removable covers called *bells*, which are lowered over the load and hearth by crane.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] An inner bell is placed over the hearth and sealed to supply a protective atmosphere.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] An outer bell is lowered to provide the heat supply.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Furnaces that are constructed in a pit and extend to floor level or slightly above are called pit furnaces.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Workpieces can be suspended from fixtures, held in baskets, or placed on bases in the furnace.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Pit furnaces are suited to heating long tubes, shafts, and rods by holding them in a vertical position.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] This manner of loading provides minimal distortion.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Salt baths are used in a wide variety of heat treatment processes including neutral hardening, liquid carburising, liquid nitriding, austempering, martempering and tempering.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Parts are loaded into a pot of molten salt where they are heated by conduction, giving a very readily available source of heat.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The core temperature of a part rises in temperature at approximately the same rate as its surface in a salt bath.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Salt baths utilize a variety of salts for heat treatment, with cyanide salts being the most extensively used.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Concerns about associated occupation health and safety, and expensive waste management and disposal due to their environmental effects have made the use of salt baths less attractive in recent years.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Consequently, many salt baths are being replaced by more environmentally friendly fluidized bed furnaces.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] A fluidised bed consists of a cylindrical retort made from high-temperature alloy, filled with sand-like aluminum oxide particulate.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] Gas (air or nitrogen) is bubbled through the oxide and the sand moves in such a way that it exhibits fluid-like behavior, hence the term *fluidized*.
[src:metallurgy/heat-treating] The solid-solid contact of the oxide gives very high thermal conductivity and excellent temperature uniformity throughout the furnace, comparable to those seen in a salt bath.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metallurgy encompasses both the science and the technology of metals, including their production and the engineering of metal components used in products for both consumers and manufacturers.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metallurgy is distinct from the craft of metalworking by providing it with a scientific foundation, much as medical science supports the practice of medicine.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] A specialist practitioner of metallurgy is known as a metallurgist.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The science of metallurgy is further subdivided into two broad categories: chemical metallurgy and physical metallurgy.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Chemical metallurgy is chiefly concerned with the reduction and oxidation of metals, and the chemical performance of metals.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Subjects of study in chemical metallurgy include mineral processing, the extraction of metals, thermodynamics, electrochemistry, and chemical degradation (corrosion).
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In contrast, physical metallurgy focuses on the mechanical properties of metals, the physical properties of metals, and the physical performance of metals.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Topics studied in physical metallurgy include crystallography, material characterization, mechanical metallurgy, phase transformations, and failure mechanisms.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Historically, metallurgy has predominantly focused on the production of metals.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metal production begins with the processing of ores to extract the metal, and includes the mixture of metals to make alloys.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metal alloys are often a blend of two or more metallic elements.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] However, non-metallic elements are often added to alloys in order to achieve properties suitable for an application.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The study of metal production is subdivided into ferrous metallurgy (also known as *black metallurgy*) and non-ferrous metallurgy, also known as colored metallurgy.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Ferrous metallurgy involves processes and alloys based on iron, while non-ferrous metallurgy involves processes and alloys based on other metals.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The production of ferrous metals accounts for 95% of world metal production.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Modern metallurgists work in both emerging and traditional areas as part of an interdisciplinary team alongside material scientists and other engineers.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Some traditional areas include mineral processing, metal production, heat treatment, failure analysis, and the joining of metals (including welding, brazing, and soldering).
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Emerging areas for metallurgists include nanotechnology, superconductors, composites, biomedical materials, electronic materials (semiconductors) and surface engineering.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In the late 19th century, metallurgy's definition was extended to the more general scientific study of metals, alloys, and related processes.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In English, the /mɛˈtælərdʒi/ pronunciation is the more common one in the United Kingdom while /ˈmɛtəlɜːrdʒi/ pronunciation is the more common one in the United States and is the first-listed variant in various American dictionaries, including *Merriam-Webster Collegiate* and *American Heritage*.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The earliest metal employed by humans appears to be gold, which can be found "native".
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Small amounts of natural gold, dating to the late Paleolithic period, 40,000 BCE, have been found in Spanish caves.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Silver, copper, tin and meteoric iron can also be found in native form, allowing a limited amount of metalworking in early cultures.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Early cold metallurgy, using native copper that was not smelted from ore has been documented at sites in Anatolia and at the site of Tell Maghzaliyah in Iraq, dating from the 7th~6th millennia BCE.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The earliest archaeological support of smelting (hot metallurgy) in Eurasia is found in the Balkans and Carpathian Mountains, as evidenced by findings of objects made by metal casting and smelting dated to around 6,200 ~ 5,000 BCE, with the invention of copper metallurgy.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Certain metals, such as tin, lead, and copper can be recovered from their ores by simply heating the rocks in a comparatively moderate-temperature fire or blast furnace in a process known as *smelting*.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The first evidence of copper smelting, dating from the 6th millennium BCE, has been found at archaeological sites in Majdanpek, Jarmovac, and Pločnik, in present-day Serbia.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The site of Pločnik has produced a smelted copper axe dating from 5,500 BCE, belonging to the Vinča culture.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The Balkans and adjacent Carpathian region were the location of major Chalcolithic cultures including Vinča, Varna, Karanovo, Gumelnița and Hamangia, which are often grouped together under the name of 'Old Europe'.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] With the Carpatho-Balkan region described as the 'earliest metallurgical province in Eurasia', its scale and technical quality of metal production in the 6th~5th millennia BCE totally overshadowed that of any other contemporary production centre.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The earliest documented use of lead (possibly native or smelted) in the Near East dates from the 6th millennium BCE, is from the late Neolithic settlements of Yarim Tepe and Arpachiyah in Iraq.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The artifacts suggest that lead smelting may have predated copper smelting.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metallurgy of lead has also been found in the Balkans during the same period.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Copper smelting is documented at sites in Anatolia and at the site of Tal-i Iblis in southeastern Iran from c.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Copper smelting is first documented in the Delta region of northern Egypt in c.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] 4,000 BCE, associated with the Maadi culture.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] This represents the earliest evidence for smelting in Africa.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The Varna Necropolis, Bulgaria, is a burial site located in the western industrial zone of Varna, approximately 4 km from the city centre, internationally considered one of the key archaeological sites in world prehistory.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The oldest gold treasure in the world, dating from 4,600 BC – 4,200 BCE, was discovered at Varna.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The gold piece dating from 4,500 BCE, found in 2019 in Durankulak, near Varna is another important example.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Other signs of early metals are found from the 3rd millennium BCE in Palmela, Portugal, Los Millares, Spain, and Stonehenge, United Kingdom.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The precise beginnings, however, have not been clearly ascertained and new discoveries are both continuous and ongoing.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In approximately 1,900 BCE, ancient iron smelting sites existed in Tamil Nadu.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In the Near East, about 3,500 BCE, it was discovered that the superior metal bronze could be made by combining copper and tin.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] This represented a major technological shift known as the Bronze Age.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The extraction of iron from its ore into a workable metal is much more difficult than for copper or tin.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The process appears to have been invented by the Hittites in about 1,200 BCE, beginning the Iron Age.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The ability to extract and work iron was a key factor in the success of the Philistines.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Historical developments in ferrous metallurgy can be found in a wide variety of past cultures and civilizations.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Wootz process was developed and practiced in the Indian subcontinent as early as 300 BCE—although certainly by 200 BCE—high quality steel was being produced in southern India, by what Europeans would later call the crucible technique.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Golconda steel, also called Wootz steel is an ultra-high carbon steel, with a natural inclusion of carbide forming Vanadium (~0.005%), resulting in the formation of nanomaterials in its microstructure and characterised by exhibiting properties such as superplasticity and high impact hardness.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Archaeological and Tamil language literary evidence suggests that this manufacturing process was already in existence in South India well before the common era, with wootz steel exported from the Chera dynasty and called *Seric Iron* in Rome, and later known as Damascus steel in Europe.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Reproduction research undertaken by Prof.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] J.D Verhoeven and Al Pendray identified the role of impurities within the local ore, in carbide formation, and repeated thermal cycling of blades, in the pattern creation, and reproduced Wootz steel blades with patterns microscopically and visually identical to ancient blade patterns.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] A 16th century book by Georg Agricola, *De re metallica*, describes the highly developed and complex processes of mining metal ores, metal extraction, and metallurgy of the time.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Agricola has been described as the "father of metallurgy".
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Extractive metallurgy is the practice of removing valuable metals from an ore and refining the extracted raw metals into a purer form.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In order to convert a metal oxide or sulphide to a purer metal, the ore must be reduced physically, chemically, or electrolytically.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Extractive metallurgists are interested in three primary streams: feed, concentrate (metal oxide/sulphide) and tailings (waste).
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] After mining, large pieces of the ore feed are broken through crushing or grinding in order to obtain particles small enough, where each particle is either mostly valuable or mostly waste.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Concentrating the particles of value in a form supporting separation enables the desired metal to be removed from waste products.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Mining may not be necessary, if the ore body and physical environment are conducive to leaching.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Leaching dissolves minerals in an ore body and results in an enriched solution.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The solution is collected and processed to extract valuable metals.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Ore bodies often contain more than one valuable metal.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Tailings of a previous process may be used as a feed in another process to extract a secondary product from the original ore.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Additionally, a concentrate may contain more than one valuable metal.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] That concentrate would then be processed to separate the valuable metals into individual constituents.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Much effort has been placed on understanding the iron–carbon alloy system, which includes steels and cast irons.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Plain carbon steels (those that contain essentially only carbon as an alloying element) are used in low-cost, high-strength applications, where neither weight nor corrosion are a major concern.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Cast irons, including ductile iron, are also part of the iron-carbon system.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Iron-Manganese-Chromium alloys (Hadfield-type steels) are also used in non-magnetic applications such as directional drilling.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Other engineering metals include aluminium, chromium, copper, magnesium, nickel, titanium, zinc, and silicon.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] These metals are most often used as alloys with the noted exception of silicon, which is not a metal.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In production engineering, metallurgy is concerned with the production of metallic components for use in consumer or engineering products.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] This involves production of alloys, shaping, heat treatment and surface treatment of product.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The metallurgist's task is to achieve balance between material properties, such as cost, weight, strength, toughness, hardness, corrosion, fatigue resistance and performance in temperature extremes.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] To achieve this goal, the operating environment must be carefully considered.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Hardness testing (using scales such as Rockwell, Vickers, and Brinell) is a common practice for characterizing a metal's elasticity and plasticity In a saltwater environment, most ferrous metals and some non-ferrous alloys corrode quickly.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metals exposed to cold or cryogenic conditions may undergo a ductile to brittle transition and lose their toughness, becoming more brittle and prone to cracking.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metals under continual cyclic loading can suffer from metal fatigue.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metals under constant stress at elevated temperatures can creep.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Cold-working processes, in which the product's shape is altered by rolling, fabrication or other processes, while the product is cold, can increase the strength of the product by a process called work hardening.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Work hardening creates microscopic defects in the metal, which resist further changes of shape.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metals can be heat-treated to alter the properties of strength, ductility, toughness, hardness and resistance to corrosion.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Often, mechanical and thermal treatments are combined in what are known as thermo-mechanical treatments for better properties and more efficient processing of materials.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] These processes are common to high-alloy special steels, superalloys and titanium alloys.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Electroplating is a chemical surface-treatment technique.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] It involves bonding a thin layer of another metal such as gold, silver, chromium or zinc to the surface of the product.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] This is done by selecting the coating material electrolyte solution, which is the material that is going to coat the workpiece (gold, silver, zinc).
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] There needs to be two electrodes of different materials: one the same material as the coating material and one that is receiving the coating material.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Two electrodes are electrically charged and the coating material is stuck to the work piece.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] It is used to reduce corrosion as well as to improve the product's aesthetic appearance.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] It is also used to make inexpensive metals look like the more expensive ones (gold, silver).
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Shot peening is a cold working process used to finish metal parts.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In the process of shot peening, small round shot is blasted against the surface of the part to be finished.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] This process is used to prolong the product life of the part, prevent stress corrosion failures, and also prevent fatigue.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The shot leaves small dimples on the surface like a peen hammer does, which cause compression stress under the dimple.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] As the shot media strikes the material over and over, it forms many overlapping dimples throughout the piece being treated.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The compression stress in the surface of the material strengthens the part and makes it more resistant to fatigue failure, stress failures, corrosion failure, and cracking.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Thermal spraying techniques are another popular finishing option, and often have better high temperature properties than electroplated coatings.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The spray treating process is known by many different names such as HVOF (*high velocity oxygen fuel*), plasma spray, flame spray, arc spray and metalizing.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Metallurgists study the microscopic and macroscopic structure of metals using metallography, a technique invented by Henry Clifton Sorby.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] In metallography, an alloy of interest is ground flat and polished to a mirror finish.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The sample can then be etched to reveal the microstructure and macrostructure of the metal.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] The sample is then examined in an optical or electron microscope, and the image contrast provides details on the composition, mechanical properties, and processing history.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Crystallography, often using diffraction of X-rays or electrons, is another valuable tool available to the modern metallurgist.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Crystallography allows identification of unknown materials and reveals the crystal structure of the sample.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Quantitative crystallography can be used to calculate the amount of phases present as well as the degree of strain to which a sample has been subjected.
[src:metallurgy/metallurgy] Current advanced characterization techniques, which are used frequently in this field are: *Scanning electron microscopy* (SEM), *transmission electron microscopy* (TEM), *electron backscatter diffraction* (EBSD) and *atom-probe tomography* (APT).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In this way, powder metallurgy can be used to make unique materials impossible to get from melting or forming in other ways.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A very important product of this type is tungsten carbide.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Tungsten carbide is used to cut and form other metals and is made from tungsten carbide particles bonded with cobalt.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Tungsten carbide is the largest and most important use of tungsten, consuming about 50% of the world supply.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Other products include sintered filters, porous oil-impregnated bearings, electrical contacts and diamond tools.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powder metallurgy techniques usually consist of the compression of a powder, and heating (sintering) it at a temperature below the melting point of the metal, to bind the particles together.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Compaction is usually done with a die press, but can also be done with explosive shocks or placing a flexible container in a high-pressure gas or liquid.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Sintering is usually done in a dedicated furnace, but can also be done in tandem with compression (hot isostatic compression), or with the use of electric currents.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Since the advent of industrial production-scale metal powder-based additive manufacturing in the 2010s, selective laser sintering and other metal additive manufacturing processes are a new category of commercially important powder metallurgy applications.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The powder metallurgy "press and sinter" process generally consists of three basic steps: powder blending (or pulverisation), die compaction, and sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Compaction of the powder in the die is generally performed at room temperature.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Sintering is the process of binding a material together with heat without liquefying it.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] It is usually conducted at atmospheric pressure and under carefully controlled atmosphere composition.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] To obtain special properties or enhanced precision, secondary processing like coining or heat treatment often follows.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] One of the older such methods is the process of blending fine (<180 microns) metal powders with additives, pressing them into a die of the desired shape, and then sintering the compressed material together, under a controlled atmosphere.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The metal powder is usually iron, and additives include a lubricant wax, carbon, copper, and/or nickel.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This produces precise parts, normally very close to the die dimensions, but with 5–15% porosity, and thus sub-wrought steel properties.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This method is still used to make around 1 Mt/y of structural components of iron-based alloys.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] There are several other PM processes that have been developed over the last fifty years.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The history of powder metallurgy and the art of metal and ceramic sintering are intimately related to each other.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Sintering involves the production of a hard solid metal or ceramic piece from a starting powder.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The ancient Incas made jewelry and other artifacts from precious metal powders, though mass manufacturing of PM products did not begin until the mid or late 19th century.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In these early manufacturing operations, iron was extracted by hand from a metal sponge following reduction and was then reintroduced as a powder for final melting or sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A much wider range of products can be obtained from powder processes than from direct alloying of fused materials.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In melting operations, the "phase rule" applies to all pure and combined elements and strictly dictates the distribution of liquid and solid phases which can exist for specific compositions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In addition, whole body melting of starting materials is required for alloying, thus imposing unwelcome chemical, thermal, and containment constraints on manufacturing.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Unfortunately, the handling of aluminium/iron powders poses major problems.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Other substances that are especially reactive with atmospheric oxygen, such as tin, are sinterable in special atmospheres or with temporary coatings.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In powder metallurgy or ceramics it is possible to fabricate components which otherwise would decompose or disintegrate.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] All considerations of solid-liquid phase changes can be ignored, so powder processes are more flexible than casting, extrusion, or forging techniques.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Controllable characteristics of products prepared using various powder technologies include mechanical, magnetic, and other unconventional properties of such materials as porous solids, aggregates, and intermetallic compounds.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Competitive characteristics of manufacturing processing (e.g. tool wear, complexity, or vendor options) also may be closely controlled.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Many special products are possible with powder metallurgy technology.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Extremely thin films and tiny spheres exhibit high strength.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] One application of this observation is to coat brittle materials in whisker form with a submicrometre film of much softer metal (e.g. cobalt-coated tungsten).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The surface strain of the thin layer places the harder metal under compression, so that when the entire composite is sintered the rupture strength increases markedly.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] With this method, strengths on the order of 2.8 GPa versus 550 MPa have been observed for, respectively, coated (25% cobalt) and uncoated tungsten carbides.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Several techniques have been developed that permit large production rates of powdered particles, often with considerable control over the size ranges of the final grain population.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powders may be prepared by crushing, grinding, chemical reactions, or electrolytic deposition.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The most commonly used powders are copper-base and iron-base materials.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powders of the elements titanium, vanadium, thorium, niobium, tantalum, calcium, and uranium have been produced by high-temperature reduction of the corresponding nitrides and carbides.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Iron, nickel, uranium, and beryllium submicrometre powders are obtained by reducing metallic oxalates and formates.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Exceedingly fine particles also have been prepared by directing a stream of molten metal through a high-temperature plasma jet or flame, atomizing the material.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Various chemical and flame-associated powdering processes are adopted in part to prevent serious degradation of particle surfaces by atmospheric oxygen.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Atomization is accomplished by forcing a molten metal stream through an orifice at moderate pressures.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A gas is introduced into the metal stream just before it leaves the nozzle, serving to create turbulence as the entrained gas expands (due to heating) and exits into a large collection volume exterior to the orifice.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The collection volume is filled with gas to promote further turbulence of the molten metal jet.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Air and powder streams are segregated using gravity or cyclonic separation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Simple atomization techniques are available in which liquid metal is forced through an orifice at a sufficiently high velocity to ensure turbulent flow.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The usual performance index used is the Reynolds number.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] At low Re the liquid jet oscillates, but at higher velocities the stream becomes turbulent and breaks into droplets.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Pumping energy is applied to droplet formation with very low efficiency (on the order of 1%) and control over the size distribution of the metal particles produced is rather poor.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Other techniques such as nozzle vibration, nozzle asymmetry, multiple impinging streams, or molten-metal injection into ambient gas are all available to increase atomization efficiency, produce finer grains, and to narrow the particle size distribution.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Unfortunately, it is difficult to eject metals through orifices smaller than a few millimeters in diameter, which in practice limits the minimum size of powder grains to approximately 10 μm.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Atomization also produces a wide spectrum of particle sizes, necessitating downstream classification by screening and remelting a significant fraction of the grain boundary.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Centrifugal disintegration of molten particles offers one way around these problems.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Extensive experience is available with iron, steel, and aluminium.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Metal to be powdered is formed into a rod which is introduced into a chamber through a rapidly rotating spindle.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Opposite the spindle tip is an electrode from which an arc is established which heats the metal rod.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] As the tip material fuses, the rapid rod rotation throws off tiny melt droplets which solidify before hitting the chamber walls.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A circulating gas sweeps particles from the chamber.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Similar techniques could be employed in space or on the Moon.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The chamber wall could be rotated to force new powders into remote collection vessels, and the electrode could be replaced by a solar mirror focused at the end of the rod.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] An alternative approach capable of producing a very narrow distribution of grain sizes but with low throughput consists of a rapidly spinning bowl heated to well above the melting point of the material to be powdered.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Liquid metal, introduced onto the surface of the basin near the center at flow rates adjusted to permit a thin metal film to skim evenly up the walls and over the edge, breaks into droplets, each approximately the thickness of the film.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Another powder-production technique involves a thin jet of liquid metal intersected by high-speed streams of atomized water which break the jet into drops and cool the powder before it reaches the bottom of the bin.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In subsequent operations the powder is dried.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Water atomization cools and solidifies the metal particles more rapidly than gas atomization.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Since the solidification rate is inversely proportional to the particle size, smaller particles can be made using water atomization.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The smaller the particles, the more homogeneous the microstructure will be.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Particles produced this way will also have a more irregular shape and the particle size distribution will be wider.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In addition, some surface contamination can occur by oxidation skin formation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powder can be reduced by some kind of pre-consolidation treatment, such as annealing used for the manufacture of ceramic tools.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powder compaction, one of the most critical steps in powder metallurgy processes, is the process of compacting metal powder through the application of high pressures.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Most powder compaction is done with mechanical presses and rigid tools, but hydraulic and pneumatic techniques can also be used, as well as methods that combine compaction with sintering, like hot isostatic compaction.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Traditional metalforming processes, including rolling, forging, extrusion, and swaging, are also used.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The density of the compacted powder increases with the amount of pressure applied.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Pressure of 10 t/in2 to 50 t/in2 (150 MPa to 700 MPa) are commonly used for metal powder compaction.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] To attain the same compression ratio across a component with more than one level or height, it is necessary to work with multiple lower punches.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A cylindrical workpiece is made by single-level tooling.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A more complex shape can be made by the common multiple-level tooling.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The dominant technology for the forming of products from powder materials, in terms of both tonnage quantities and numbers of parts produced, is die pressing.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] There are mechanical, servo-electrical and hydraulic presses available in the market, whereby the biggest powder throughput is processed by hydraulic presses.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Compaction of the powder within the die with punches to form the compact.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Generally, compaction pressure is applied through punches from both ends of the toolset in order to reduce the level of density gradient within the compact.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Ejection of the compact from the die, using the lower punch(es) withdrawal from the die.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Removal of the compact from the upper face of the die using the fill shoe in the fill stage of the next cycle, or an automation system or robot.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Typically the tools are held in the vertical orientation with the punch tool forming the bottom of the cavity.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Probably the most basic consideration is being able to remove the part from the die after it is pressed, along with avoiding sharp corners in the design.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Keeping the maximum surface area below 20 square inches (0.013 m2) and the height-to-diameter ratio below 7-to-1 is recommended.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Along with having walls thicker than 0.08 inches (2.0 mm) and keeping the adjacent wall thickness ratios below 2.5-to-1.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] One of the major advantages of this process is its ability to produce complex geometries.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Parts with undercuts and threads require a secondary machining operation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Typical part sizes range from 0.1 square inches (0.65 cm2) to 20 square inches (130 cm2). in area and from 0.1 to 4 inches (0.25 to 10.16 cm) in length.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] However, it is possible to produce parts that are less than 0.1 square inches (0.65 cm2) and larger than 25 square inches (160 cm2). in area and from a fraction of an inch (2.54 cm) to approximately 8 inches (20 cm) in length.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Small mechanical presses can generally compact about 100 pieces per minute.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In die compaction, there are four major classes of tool styles: single-action compaction, used for thin, flat components; opposed double-action with two punch motions, which accommodates thicker components; double-action with floating die; and double-action withdrawal die.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Double action classes give much better density distribution than single action.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Tooling must be designed so that it will withstand the extreme pressure without deforming or bending.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Tools must be made from materials that are polished and wear-resistant.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Shock consolidation, or dynamic consolidation, is an experimental technique of consolidating powders using high pressure shock waves.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This technique is useful for very large products, including those over 3000 tons and larger than 100 square inches.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] These are commonly produced by impacting the workpiece with an explosively accelerated plate.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Despite being researched for a long time, the technique still has some problems in controllability and uniformity.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] However, it offers some valuable potential advantages.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] As an example, consolidation occurs so rapidly that metastable microstructures may be retained.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Isostatic powder compacting is an alternate method of powder compaction.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In cold isostatic compaction, fine metal particles are placed into a flexible mould, which is then immersed in a high-pressure gas or liquid from all directions (isostatic).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] After sintering, this manufacturing process produces very little scrap metal and can be used to make many different shapes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The tolerances that this process can achieve in combination with sintering are very precise, ranging from +/- 0.008 inches (0.2 mm) for axial dimensions and +/- 0.020 inches (0.5 mm) for radial dimensions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This is the most efficient type of powder compacting (the following subcategories are also from this reference).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This operation is generally only applicable on small production quantities, and although the cost of a mold is much lower than that of pressing dies, it is generally not reusable and the production time is much longer.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Production rates are usually very low, but parts weighing up to 100 pounds can be effectively compacted.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Because pressure is applied from all directions, lower compaction pressures are required to produce higher densities of powder in the end product.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The density of isostatic compacted parts is 5% to 10% higher than with other powder metallurgy processes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] It is possible to compact workpieces that are between 0.0625 in (1.59 mm) and 5 in (127 mm) thick and 0.0625 in (1.59 mm) to 40 in (1,016 mm) long.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Advantages over standard powder compaction are the possibility of thinner walls and larger workpieces.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The height-to-diameter ratio has no limitation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] No specific limitations exist in wall thickness variations, undercuts, reliefs, threads, and cross holes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] No lubricants are needed for isostatic powder compaction.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The minimum wall thickness is 0.05 inches (1.27 mm) and the product can have a weight between 40 and 300 pounds (18 and 136 kg).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] There is 25 to 45% shrinkage of the powder after compacting.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Isostatic tools are available in three styles, free mold (wet-bag), coarse mold (damp-bag), and fixed mold (dry-bag).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The free mold style is the traditional style of isostatic compaction and is not generally used for high production work.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In free mold tooling the mold is removed and filled outside the canister.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Damp bag is where the mold is located in the canister, yet filled outside.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In fixed mold tooling, the mold is contained within the canister, which facilitates automation of the process.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] After compaction, powdered materials are heated in a controlled atmosphere in a process known as sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] During this process, the surfaces of the particles are bonded and desirable properties are achieved.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Sintering of powder metals is a process in which particles under pressure chemically bond to themselves in order to form a coherent shape when exposed to a high temperature.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The temperature in which the particles are sintered is most commonly below the melting point of the main component in the powder.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] If the temperature is above the melting point of a component in the powder metal part, the liquid of the melted particles fills the pores.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This type of sintering is known as liquid-state sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A major challenge with sintering in general is knowing the effect of the process on the dimensions of the compact particles.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This is especially difficult for tooling purposes in which specific dimensions may be needed.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] It is most common for the sintered part to shrink and become denser, but it can also expand or experience no net change.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The main driving force for solid-state sintering is an excess of surface-free energy.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The process of solid-state sintering is complex and dependent on the material and furnace (temperature and gas) conditions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] There are six main stages that sintering processes can be grouped in which may overlap with one another: 1 initial bonding among particles, 2) neck growth, 3) pore channel closure, 4) pore rounding, 5) densification or pore shrinkage, and 6) pore coarsening.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The main mechanisms present in these stages are evaporation, condensation, grain boundaries, volume diffusion, and plastic deformation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] During this process, a number of characteristics are increased including the strength, ductility, toughness, and electrical and thermal conductivity of the material.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] If different elemental powders are compact and sintered, the material would form into alloys and intermetallic phases.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] As the pore sizes decrease, the density of the material will increase.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] As stated above, this shrinkage is a huge problem in making parts or tooling in which particular dimensions are required.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The shrinkage of test materials is monitored and used to manipulate the furnace conditions or to oversize the compact materials in order to achieve the desired dimensions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Although, sintering does not deplete the compact part of porosity.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In general, powder metal parts contain five to twenty-five percent porosity after sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Most sintering furnaces contain three zones with three different properties that help to carry out the six steps above.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The first zone, commonly coined the burn-off or purge stage, is designed to combust air, burn any contaminants such as lubricant or binders, and slowly raise the temperature of the compact materials.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] If the temperature of the compact parts is raised too quickly, the air in the pores will be at a very high internal pressure which could lead to expansion or fracture of the part.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The second zone, known as the high-temperature stage, is used to produce solid-state diffusion and particle bonding.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The material is seeking to lower its surface energy and does so by moving toward the points of contact between particles.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The contact points become larger and eventually a solid mass with small pores is created.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The third zone, also called the cooling period, is used to cool down the parts while still in a controlled atmosphere.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This is an important zone as it prevents oxidation from immediate contact with the air or a phenomenon known as rapid cooling.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] All of the three stages must be carried out in a controlled atmosphere containing no oxygen.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Hydrogen, nitrogen, dissociated ammonia, and cracked hydrocarbons are common gases pumped into the furnace zones providing a reducing atmosphere, preventing oxide formation.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Hot isostatic pressing (HIP) compresses and sinters the part simultaneously by applying heat on the order of 2300 °F (1250 °C), in the case of iron, or 2750 °F (1500 °C) in the case of nickel alloys.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] This procedure, together with explosion-driven compressive techniques is used extensively in the production of high-temperature and high-strength parts such as turbine disks for jet engines.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In most applications of powder metallurgy the compact is hot-pressed, heated to a temperature above which the materials cannot remain work-hardened.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Hot pressing lowers the pressures required to reduce porosity and speeds welding and grain deformation processes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] It also permits better dimensional control of the product, lessens sensitivity to physical characteristics of starting materials, and allows powder to be compressed to higher densities than with cold pressing, resulting in higher strength.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Negative aspects of hot pressing include shorter die life, slower throughput because of powder heating, and the frequent necessity for protective atmospheres or simple vacuum during forming and cooling stages.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] HIP produces products often of higher quality than other processes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] These techniques employ electric currents to drive or enhance sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] A combination of mechanical pressure and electrical current, passed through either the powder or the container, significantly reduces the sintering time compared to conventional solutions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Resistance sintering techniques include spark plasma sintering (SPS), plasma-activated sintering (PAS), and pulse electric current sintering (PECS). electric discharge sintering techniques include capacitor discharge sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Currently, spark plasma sintering is currently the most commonly used method of electric pulse consolidation in general.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Resistance sintering currents usually reach about 1 kA per square centimer, while electric discharge sintering voltages of up to several kilovolts also require very high currents, over 10 kA per square centimer.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Resistance sintering techniques are consolidation methods based on temperature, where heating of the mold and of the powders is accomplished through electric currents, usually with a characteristic processing time of 15 to 30 minutes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] On the other hand, electric discharge sintering methods rely on high-density currents (from 0.1 to 1 kA/mm2) to directly sinter electrically conductive powders, with a characteristic time between tens of microseconds to hundreds of milliseconds.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Strictly, the phrase "continuous process" should be used only to describe modes of manufacturing which could be extended indefinitely in time.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Normally, however, the term refers to processes whose products are much longer in one physical dimension than in the other two.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Compression, rolling, and extrusion are the most common examples.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In a simple compression process, powder flows from a bin onto a two-walled channel and is repeatedly compressed vertically by a horizontally stationary punch.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] After stripping the compress from the conveyor, the compacted mass is introduced into a sintering furnace.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] An even easier approach is to spray powder onto a moving belt and sinter it without compression.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] However, good methods for stripping cold-pressed materials from moving belts are hard to find.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] One alternative that avoids the belt-stripping difficulty altogether is the manufacture of metal sheets using opposed hydraulic rams, although weakness lines across the sheet may arise during successive press operations.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Powders can also be rolled to produce sheets.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The powdered metal is fed into a two-high rolling mill, and is compacted into strip form at up to 100 feet per minute (0.5 m/s).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The strip is then sintered and subjected to another rolling and further sintering.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Rolling is commonly used to produce sheet metal for electrical and electronic components, as well as coins.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Considerable work also has been done on rolling multiple layers of different materials simultaneously into sheets.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Extrusion processes are of two general types.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] In one type, the powder is mixed with a binder or plasticizer at room temperature; in the other, the powder is extruded at elevated temperatures without fortification.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Extrusions with binders are used extensively in the preparation of tungsten-carbide composites.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Tubes, complex sections, and spiral drill shapes are manufactured in extended lengths and diameters varying in the range 0.5–300 mm (0.020–11.811 in).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Hard metal wires of 0.1 mm (0.0039 in) diameter have been drawn from powder stock.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] At the opposite extreme, large extrusions on a tonnage basis may be feasible.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] For softer, easier-to-form metals such as aluminium and copper alloys continuous extrusion may also be performed using processes such as conform or continuous rotary extrusion.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] These processes use a rotating wheel with a groove around its circumference to drive the loose powder through a forming die.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Through a combination of high pressure and a complex strain path the powder particles deform, generate a large amount of frictional heat and bond together to form a bulk solid.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Theoretically, fully continuous operation is possible as long as the powder can be fed into the process.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] There appears to be no limitation to the variety of metals and alloys that can be extruded, provided the temperatures and pressures involved are within the capabilities of die materials.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Extrusion lengths may range from 3 to 30 m and diameters from 0.2 to 1 m.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Modern presses are largely automatic and operate at high speeds (on the order of m/s).
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The special materials and processes used in powder metallurgy can pose hazards to life and property.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] The high surface-area-to-volume ratio of the powders can increase their chemical reactivity in biological exposures (for example, inhalation or ingestion), and increases the risk of dust explosions.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Metals that are generally unreactive can quickly catch fire when the surface area is high.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] For instance, steel is generally not flammable, but steel wool quickly catches fire.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Materials considered relatively benign in bulk can pose special toxicological risks when in a finely divided form.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Inhalation of heavy metals can result in many health issues.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Lead and cadmium are generally toxic, and cobalt can cause asthma and fibrosis in sensitive individuals.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Aluminium powders are known to cause lung fibrosis among people who work with it in manufacturing plants.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] According to the CDC, workers who are exposed to large amounts of aluminium can have other lung problems and abnormal chest X-rays.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Some workers have also had decreased performance in neurological tests.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Exposure to aluminum can irritate the skin and eyes.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Aluminium powder is also highly flammable.
[src:metallurgy/powder-metallurgy] Besides the risks of metal powder itself, there are many hazards during the production process as well.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] In materials science, **quenching** is the rapid cooling of a workpiece in water, gas, oil, polymer, air, or other fluids to obtain certain material properties.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] A type of heat treating, quenching prevents undesired low-temperature processes, such as phase transformations, from occurring.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] It does this by reducing the window of time during which these undesired reactions are both thermodynamically favorable and kinetically accessible; for instance, quenching can reduce the crystal grain size of both metallic and plastic materials, increasing their hardness.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] In metallurgy, quenching is most commonly used to harden steel by inducing a martensite transformation, where the steel must be rapidly cooled through its eutectoid point, the temperature at which austenite becomes unstable.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Rapid cooling prevents the formation of cementite structure, instead forcibly dissolving carbon atoms in the ferrite lattice.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] In steel alloyed with metals such as nickel and manganese, the eutectoid temperature becomes much lower, but the kinetic barriers to phase transformation remain the same.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] This allows quenching to start at a lower temperature, making the process much easier.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] High-speed steel also has added tungsten, which serves to raise kinetic barriers, which, among other effects, gives material properties (hardness and abrasion resistance) as though the workpiece had been cooled more rapidly than it really has.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Even cooling such alloys slowly in the air has most of the desired effects of quenching; high-speed steel weakens much less from heat cycling due to high-speed cutting.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Extremely rapid cooling can prevent the formation of all crystal structures, resulting in amorphous metal or "metallic glass".
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Quench hardening is a mechanical process in which steel and cast iron alloys are strengthened and hardened.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] These metals consist of ferrous metals and alloys.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] This is done by heating the material to a certain temperature, depending on the material.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] This produces a harder material by either surface hardening or through-hardening varying on the rate at which the material is cooled.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The material is then often tempered to reduce the brittleness that may increase from the quench hardening process.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Items that may be quenched include gears, shafts, and wear blocks.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Before hardening, cast steels and iron are of a uniform and lamellar (or layered) pearlitic grain structure.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] This is a mixture of ferrite and cementite formed when steel or cast iron are manufactured and cooled at a slow rate.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Pearlite is not an ideal material for many common applications of steel alloys as it is quite soft.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] By heating pearlite past its eutectoid transition temperature of 727 °C and then rapidly cooling, some of the material's crystal structure can be transformed into a much harder structure known as martensite.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Steels with this martensitic structure are often used in applications when the workpiece must be highly resistant to deformation, such as the cutting edge of blades.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The process of quenching is a progression, beginning with heating the sample.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Most materials are heated to between 815 and 900 °C (1,499 and 1,652 °F), with careful attention paid to keeping temperatures throughout the workpiece uniform.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Minimizing uneven heating and overheating is key to imparting desired material properties.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The second step in the quenching process is soaking.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Workpieces can be soaked in air (air furnace), a liquid bath, or a vacuum.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The recommended time allocation in salt or lead baths is up to 6 minutes.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Soaking times can range a little higher within a vacuum.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] As in the heating step, it is important that the temperature throughout the sample remains as uniform as possible during soaking.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Once the workpiece has finished soaking, it moves on to the cooling step.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] During this step, the part is submerged into some kind of quenching fluid; different quenching fluids can have a significant effect on the final characteristics of a quenched part.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Water is one of the most efficient quenching media where maximum hardness is desired, but there is a small chance that it may cause distortion and tiny cracking.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] When hardness can be sacrificed, mineral oils are often used.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] These oil-based fluids often oxidize and form sludge during quenching, which consequently lowers the efficiency of the process.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The cooling rate of oil is much less than water.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Intermediate rates between water and oil can be obtained with a purpose-formulated quenchant, a substance with an inverse solubility that therefore deposits on the object to slow the rate of cooling.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Quenching can also be accomplished using inert gases, such as nitrogen and noble gases.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Nitrogen is commonly used at greater than atmospheric pressure ranging up to 20 bar absolute.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Helium is also used because its thermal capacity is greater than nitrogen.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Alternatively, argon can be used; however, its density requires significantly more energy to move, and its thermal capacity is less than the alternatives.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] To minimize distortion in the workpiece, long cylindrical workpieces are quenched vertically; flat workpieces are quenched on the edge; and thick sections should enter the bath first.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] To prevent steam bubbles the bath is agitated.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Often, after quenching, an iron or steel alloy will be excessively hard and brittle due to an overabundance of martensite.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] In these cases, another heat treatment technique known as tempering is performed on the quenched material to increase the toughness of iron-based alloys.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Tempering is usually performed after hardening, to reduce some of the excess hardness, and is done by heating the metal to some temperature below the critical point for a certain period of time, then allowing it to cool in still air.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] During this stage, due to the Leidenfrost effect, the object is fully surrounded by vapor which insulates it from the rest of the liquid.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Once the temperature has dropped enough, the vapor layer will destabilize and the liquid will be able to fully contact the object and heat will be removed much more quickly.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] This stage occurs when the temperature of the object is below the boiling point of the liquid.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] There is evidence of the use of quenching processes by blacksmiths stretching back into the middle of the Iron Age, but little detailed information exists related to the development of these techniques and the procedures employed by early smiths.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The earliest examples of quenched steel may come from ancient Mesopotamia, with a relatively secure example of a fourth-century BC quench-hardened chisel from Al Mina in Turkey.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] However, it is not beyond doubt that the passage describes deliberate quench-hardening, rather than simply cooling.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Likewise, there is a prospect that the *Mahabharata* refers to the oil-quenching of iron arrowheads, but the evidence is problematic.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Pliny the Elder addressed the topic of quenchants, distinguishing the water of different rivers.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] Chapters 18–21 of the twelfth-century *De diversis artis* by Theophilus Presbyter mentions quenching, recommending amongst other things that 'tools are also given a harder tempering in the urine of a small, red-headed boy than in ordinary water'.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] One of the fuller early discussions of quenching is the first Western printed book on metallurgy, *Von Stahel und Eysen*, published in 1532, which is characteristic of late-medieval technical treatises.
[src:metallurgy/quenching] The modern scientific study of quenching began to gain real momentum from the seventeenth century, with a major step being the observation-led discussion by Giambattista della Porta in his 1558 *Magia Naturalis*.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Sulfide ores such as those commonly used to obtain copper, zinc, or lead, are roasted before smelting in order to convert the sulfides to oxides, which are more readily reduced to the metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Roasting heats the ore in the presence of oxygen from air, oxidizing the ore and liberating the sulfur as sulfur dioxide gas.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelting most prominently takes place in a blast furnace to produce pig iron, which is converted into steel.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Plants for the electrolytic reduction of aluminium are referred to as aluminium smelters.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelters can be classified into two types depending on their business model; custom smelters and integrated smelters.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] A custom smelter is a smelter that treats ore on behalf of customers or buys ore for treatment.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Custom smelters obtain ore concentrates from mines of different ownership.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Integrated smelters depend directly on a specific mining operation and tend to be located next to a mine.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelting involves more than just melting the metal out of its ore.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Most ores comprise chemical compounds of the metal and other elements, such as oxygen (as an oxide), sulfur (as a sulfide), or carbon and oxygen together (as a carbonate).
[src:metallurgy/smelting] To extract the metal, workers must make these compounds undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelting, therefore, consists of using suitable reducing substances that combine with those oxidizing elements to free the metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In the case of sulfides and carbonates, a process called "roasting" removes the unwanted carbon or sulfur, leaving an oxide, which is more suitable for reduction to metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Roasting is usually carried out in an oxidizing environment.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] For sulfide ores, roasting results in replacement of sulfide, partly or completely, by oxide.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Reduction is the final, high-temperature step in smelting, in which the oxide becomes the elemental metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] A reducing environment (often provided by carbon monoxide, made by incomplete combustion in an air-starved furnace) pulls the final oxygen atoms from the raw metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The carbon source acts as a chemical reactant to remove oxygen from the ore, yielding the purified metal element as a product.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The carbon source is oxidized in two stages.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] First, carbon (C) combusts with oxygen (O2) in the air to produce carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Second, the carbon monoxide reacts with the ore (e.g.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Fe2O3) and removes one of its oxygen atoms, releasing carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:metallurgy/smelting] After successive interactions with carbon monoxide, all of the oxygen in the ore will be removed, leaving the raw metal element (e.g.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] As most ores are impure, it is often necessary to use flux, such as limestone (or dolomite), to remove the accompanying rock gangue as slag.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] This calcination reaction emits carbon dioxide.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The required temperature varies both in absolute terms and in terms of the melting point of the base metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Fluxes are materials added to the ore during smelting to catalyze the desired reactions and to chemically bind to unwanted impurities or reaction products.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Calcium carbonate or calcium oxide in the form of lime are often used for this purpose, since they react with sulfur, phosphorus, and silicon impurities to allow them to be readily separated and discarded, in the form of slag.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Fluxes may also serve to control the viscosity and neutralize unwanted acids.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Flux and slag can provide a secondary service after the reduction step is complete; they provide a molten cover on the purified metal, preventing contact with oxygen while still hot enough to readily oxidize.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] This prevents impurities from forming in the metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The ores of base metals are often sulfides.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In recent centuries, reverberatory furnaces have been used to keep the charge being smelted separately from the fuel.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Traditionally, they were used for the first step of smelting: forming two liquids, one an oxide slag containing most of the impurities, and the other a sulfide matte containing the valuable metal sulfide and some impurities.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Such "reverb" furnaces are today about 40 meters long, 3 meters high, and 10 meters wide.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Fuel is burned at one end to melt the dry sulfide concentrates (usually after partial roasting) which are fed through openings in the roof of the furnace.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The slag floats over the heavier matte and is removed and discarded or recycled.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The sulfide matte is then sent to the converter.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The precise details of the process vary from one furnace to another depending on the mineralogy of the ore body.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] While reverberatory furnaces produced slags containing very little copper, they were relatively energy inefficient and off-gassed a low concentration of sulfur dioxide that was difficult to capture; a new generation of copper smelting technologies has supplanted them.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] More recent furnaces exploit bath smelting, top-jetting lance smelting, flash smelting, and blast furnaces.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Some examples of bath smelters include the Noranda furnace, the Isasmelt furnace, the Teniente reactor, the Vunyukov smelter, and the SKS technology.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Top-jetting lance smelters include the Mitsubishi smelting reactor.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Flash smelters account for over 50% of the world's copper smelters.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] There are many more varieties of smelting processes, including the Kivset, Ausmelt, Tamano, EAF, and BF.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Of the seven metals known in antiquity, only gold regularly occurs in nature as a native metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The others – copper, lead, silver, tin, iron, and mercury – occur primarily as minerals, although native copper is occasionally found in commercially significant quantities.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] These minerals are primarily carbonates, sulfides, or oxides of the metal, mixed with other components such as silica and alumina.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Roasting the carbonate and sulfide minerals in the air converts them to oxides.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The oxides, in turn, are smelted into the metal.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Carbon monoxide was (and is) the reducing agent of choice for smelting.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] It is easily produced during the heating process, and as a gas comes into intimate contact with the ore.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In the Old World, humans learned to smelt metals in prehistoric times, more than 8000 years ago.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The discovery and use of the "useful" metals – copper and bronze at first, then iron a few millennia later – had an enormous impact on human society.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The impact was so pervasive that scholars traditionally divide ancient history into Stone Age, Bronze Age, and Iron Age.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In the Americas, pre-Inca civilizations of the central Andes in Peru had mastered the smelting of copper and silver at least six centuries before the first Europeans arrived in the 16th century, while never mastering the smelting of metals such as iron for use with weapon craft.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Copper was the first metal to be smelted.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] How the discovery came about is debated.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Campfires are about 200 °C short of the temperature needed, so some propose that the first smelting of copper may have occurred in pottery kilns.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The earliest current evidence of copper smelting, dating from between 5500 BC and 5000 BC, has been found in Pločnik and Belovode, Serbia.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] A mace head found in Turkey and dated to 5000 BC, once thought to be the oldest evidence, now appears to be hammered, native copper.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Copper–tin bronzes, harder, and more durable, were developed around 3500 BC, also in Asia Minor.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] At present-day the direct product of copper smelters is anode copper which has a purity ranging from 98.5 to 99.8%.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Anode copper can then be electrorefined to produce cathode copper with a purity of 99.99%.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The earliest known cast lead beads were thought to be in the Çatalhöyük site in Anatolia (Turkey), and dated from about 6500 BC.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] However, recent research has discovered that this was not lead, but rather cerussite and galena, minerals rich in, but distinct from, lead.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Since the discovery happened several millennia before the invention of writing, there is no written record of how it was made.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] However, tin and lead can be smelted by placing the ores in a wood fire, leaving the possibility that the discovery may have occurred by accident.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Recent scholarship however has called this find into question.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Lead is a common metal, but its discovery had relatively little impact in the ancient world.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] It is too soft to use for structural elements or weapons, though its high density relative to other metals makes it ideal for sling projectiles.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] However, since it was easy to cast and shape, workers in the classical world of Ancient Greece and Ancient Rome used it extensively to pipe and store water.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] They also used it as a mortar in stone buildings.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Tin was much less common than lead, is only marginally harder, and had even less impact by itself.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The earliest evidence for iron-making is a small number of iron fragments with the appropriate amounts of carbon admixture found in the Proto-Hittite layers at Kaman-Kalehöyük and dated to 2200–2000 BC.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Souckova-Siegolová (2001) shows that iron implements were made in Central Anatolia in very limited quantities around 1800 BC and were in general use by elites, though not by commoners, during the New Hittite Empire (~1400–1200 BC).
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Archaeologists have found indications of iron working in Ancient Egypt, somewhere between the Third Intermediate Period and 23rd Dynasty (ca.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Significantly though, they have found no evidence of iron ore smelting in any (pre-modern) period.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In addition, very early instances of carbon steel were in production around 2000 years ago (around the first-century.) in northwest Tanzania, based on complex preheating principles.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] These discoveries are significant for the history of metallurgy.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Most early processes in Europe and Africa involved smelting iron ore in a bloomery, where the temperature is kept low enough so that the iron does not melt.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] This produces a spongy mass of iron called a bloom, which then must be consolidated with a hammer to produce wrought iron.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Some of the earliest evidence to date for the bloomery smelting of iron is found at Tell Hammeh, Jordan, radiocarbon-dated to c.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Lejja, a village in Nsukka, Enugu State, Nigeria, is recorded to have engaged in iron smelting as far back as pre-2000 BC.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] From the medieval period, an indirect process began to replace the direct reduction in bloomeries.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] This used a blast furnace to make pig iron, which then had to undergo a further process to make forgeable bar iron.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Processes for the second stage include fining in a finery forge.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In the 13th century during the High Middle Ages the blast furnace was introduced by China, which had been using it since as early as 200 b.c during the Qin dynasty.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Puddling was also introduced in the Industrial Revolution.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Both processes are now obsolete, and wrought iron is now rarely made.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Instead, mild steel is produced from a Bessemer converter or by other means including smelting reduction processes such as the Corex Process.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelting has serious effects on the environment, producing wastewater and slag and releasing such toxic metals as copper, silver, iron, cobalt, and selenium into the atmosphere.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Smelters also release gaseous sulfur dioxide, contributing to acid rain, which acidifies soil and water.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] The smelter in Flin Flon, Canada was one of the largest point sources of mercury in North America in the 20th century.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Even after smelter releases were drastically reduced, landscape re-emission continued to be a major regional source of mercury.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Lakes will likely receive mercury contamination from the smelter for decades, from both re-emissions returning as rainwater and leaching of metals from the soil.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Air pollutants generated by aluminium smelters include carbonyl sulfide, hydrogen fluoride, polycyclic compounds, lead, nickel, manganese, polychlorinated biphenyls, and mercury.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Copper smelter emissions include arsenic, beryllium, cadmium, chromium, lead, manganese, and nickel.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Lead smelters typically emit arsenic, antimony, cadmium, and various lead compounds.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Wastewater pollutants discharged by iron and steel mills includes gasification products such as benzene, naphthalene, anthracene, cyanide, ammonia, phenols, and cresols, together with a range of more complex organic compounds known collectively as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH).
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Treatment technologies include recycling of wastewater; settling basins, clarifiers and filtration systems for solids removal; oil skimmers and filtration; chemical precipitation and filtration for dissolved metals; carbon adsorption and biological oxidation for organic pollutants; and evaporation.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Pollutants generated by other types of smelters varies with the base metal ore.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] For example, aluminum smelters typically generate fluoride, benzo(a)pyrene, antimony, and nickel, as well as aluminum.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Copper smelters typically discharge cadmium, lead, zinc, arsenic, and nickel, in addition to copper.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Lead smelters may discharge antimony, asbestos, cadmium, copper, and zinc, in addition to lead.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] Labourers working in the smelting industry have reported respiratory illnesses inhibiting their ability to perform the physical tasks demanded by their jobs.
[src:metallurgy/smelting] In the United States, the Environmental Protection Agency has published pollution control regulations for smelters.
